{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/0028060172A/1938032001/0146.xml":{"full_text":"PLOT MUONS\nRussia Would Be Fascist\nif Plan Had Succeeded,\nTroyanovsky Says.\nA defense of the Soviet govern\nment's severity in dealing with the\nformer bolshevik leaders convicted\nof treason in the recent Moscow\ntrial is presented here by the Soviet\nAmbassador to the United States in\nan interview obtained by a noted\njournalist and commentator on\nforeign affairs. The writer, born\nin Russia and educated in the\nUnited States, served for many\nyears as foreign correspondent for\newN York and Chicago newspapers.\nBy ELIAS TOBENKIN.\nWith the curtain rung down on the\nBukhann-Rykov trial in Moscow by\nthe summary execution of 18 of the\n21 accused, Alexander A, Troyanovsky,\nSoviet Ambassador to the United\nStates, in an exclusive interview with\nthe writer defended the severity of\nthe Soviet government in refusing to\ncommute the sentence of a single\none of the 18 defendants from death\nto imprisonment, despite their own\nand international pleas for clemency.\nHad their plots not been disclosed\nin time, Russia would today be where\nAustria is. under the yoke of a\nFascist ruler.\" Mr. Troyanovsky said.\n\"We cannot be soft toward individual\ncriminals for the mere reason that,\nin the past, through our generosity,\nthpy occupied high positions in our\ngovernment. Their crimes are all the\nmore unpardonable because they mis\nused the great confidence placed in\nthem.\nDefeat in War.\n\u201cAs part of their program for up\nsetting the Soviet regime,\u201d the Am\nbassador continued, \"these men were\nplanning to force Russia into a de\nfeat in war, expecting that such a\ndefeat would aid them in their counter\nrevolutionary plans. That was the\nsignificance of the tie-up of these\nplotters with Gen. Tukhachevsky and\nthe seven other generals whom the\nSoviet government found it necessary\nsummarily to remove and execute.\n\"If Rykov, Bukharin and their co\nconspirators had been successful, they\nwould make a scrap of paper of the\nFranco-Soviet treaty and the Soviet\nUnion would at once be withdrawn\nfrom the coalition of democratic na\ntions. They would have changed\nRussia into a Fascist state, if they\nhad had the opportunity.\u201d\nMr. Troyanovsky stated that the\npleas for clemency made for Alexei\nRykov, Nikolai Bukharin and their 19\nfellow conspirators by liberals in the\nUnited States were the result of either\n\u201chonest misunderstanding\u201d or else\n\u201cbitter hostility\u201d toward the Soviet\nUnion as a land of peace and progress.\nCompare Loss of Life.\n\u201cCompare the lass of life as a re\nsult of the last trial,\u201d he said, \"with\nthe loss of life which would have ac\ncrued to Russia's 170,000.000 people\nif the foreign and domestic plots of\nthese conspirators had not been un\nearthed. exposed and punished. How\ncan we punish severely the soldiers of\nthe rank and file who during wartime\nshow cowardice and weakness if we\nare not severe toward former com\nmissars and high officials? What\nexample would we set for the fighters\nfor liberty and a better future in\nSpain and in China and to our own\nsoldiers who are ready to fight against\naggression if they should be involved\nIn war?\n\"If their plots had succeeded.\u201d the\nAmbassador said, \u201cand w-e had fol\nlowed their methods in foreign affairs,\nRussia would today be sharing the\nfate of China, Spain or Austria. Our\ngovernment, recognized the responsi\nbility not only before our own people,\nbut before the entire world. The So\nviet Union has determined to be\nstrong and firm against all its ene\nmies and hostile elements. When the\nblood of thousands upon thousands of\nSpaniards and Chinese victims of\nreaction is shed, and when countries\ndisappear from the maps of the world,\nour country cannot be lenient toward\ntraitors and conspirators in our midst.\u201d\nEspionage Activities.\nMr. Troyanovsky explained the es\npionage activities of Rykov, Bukharin\nand the others in their group by \u201cthe\nfact that they had no support from\nthe masses.\u201d They therefore sought\nassistance from abroad.\n\"Realizing, that theirs was a lost\ncause.\" Mr. Troyanovsky said, \u201cbut\nthat they would have to pay for it\nwith their lives when they were found\nout, they decided to risk everything.\nIf, for instance, they could embroil\nRussia in a defeat in this war, they\nfigured they might save themselves\nand realize their counter-revolution\nary aim. Hence the two arms of their\ntreasonable activity: Sabotage of the\nheavy industries which are essential\nto the successful pursuit of war, on\nthe one hand, and treasonable rela\ntions with foreign governments, on\nthe other.\u201d\nMr. Troyanovsky was asked about\nthe sabotage activities ascribed to the\nRykov-Bukharin group.\nDeliberate Mismanagement.\n\u201cBy deliberate mismanagement.\u201d he\nreplied, \u201cand for the sole purpose of\ndiscrediting the Stalin regime, these\nmen have retarded the coal industry\nand have disorganized the railroads\nof the country. How did they bring\nthese things about? By taking ad\nvantage of their high positions to give\nWTong orders, to countermand existing\nplans and by other deliberate mis\nmanagement.\u201d\nHe w-as asked for specific examples\nOf such sabotage.\n\u201cLet us take the chemical industry,\u201d\nMr. Troyanovsky said. \u201cI am no\nchemist and w'ill therefore speak in\ngeneral terms. The chemical industry\nrequires as a base a certain type of\nsoda. In the original plans for this\nIndustry provision was made for the\nbuilding of plants to manufacture soda.\nPiatakov (G. L. Piatokov, former as\nsistant commissar of heavy Industry,\nwho was executed in 1937), as the\nhead of this particular branch of\n1 heavy industry, countermanded these\nplans. He stated that he had other\nplants for obtaining soda. Three years\npassed. The chemical industry began\ngoing to seed because there was no\nsoda and plants to manufacture soda.\nThat was deliberate sabotage!\nEnemies Had Other Ways.\n\"There are other ways,\" the Am\nbassador continued, \"in which the\nenemies of the Soviet regime sought to\ndiscredit it. In some cases, for ex\nample, they built factories, but made\nno provision for housing the work\nmen that were to be employed in\nthese factories. Or else they built\nworkmen's houses, but neglected what\nwe call canalization and what is known\nin this country as plumbing. All this\nwas done for the purpose of discredit\ning the Soviet regime, of making the\nBombs Shatter Barcelona\nScenes like this, showing inhabitants of Barcelona hurrying past a bomb-wrecked, street\ncar have become commonplace during the intensive insurgent bombing. There remained 640\nshattered bodies of those killed in three days. T his photo sent from London to New York by radio.\n\u2014Copyright, A. P. Wirephoto.\nHitler, Master of Strategy\nReichsfuehrer Has Timed Moves in Orderto Avoid Use of Force\nin Expansion.\n.__ A__\nThe peace of the world today lies\nin the palm of the hand of Adolf\nHitler. John Lear. Associated Press\nstaff writer, analyzes Der Fuehrer's\ncareer in a series of two articles,\nof which this is the first; the sec\nond, next Sunday.\nBy JOHN LEAR.\nAssociated Press Staff Writer.\nNEW YORK, March 19\u2014Adolf\nHitler began as a poor paper\nhanger and is now the ruler\nof 75.000.000 people.\nI He defies the world.\nHe builds an empire across the pro\ntests of the biggest powers on the\nglobe, and finds nothing in his path\ni but talk.\nHow does he do it?\nThe answer is that Hitler is one\nof the most amazing strategists in\nhistory.\nHis overnight dissolution of the\nAustrian nation is but one example\nof his astuteness in maneuvering\nacross the chessboard of world politics.\nSurprise is ode of his biggest\nweapons.\nHe made his first startling use of\nit during the World War, as a dis\nj patch runner for a Bavarian regi\nment.\nCaptured French Detachment.\nHe and another dispatch bearer\nj were alone on the front in 1915. when\nthey heard a detachment of French\nsoldiers coming out of the ruins of a\nj building.\nShouting to an unaginary platoon\ni to follow them. Hitler and his pal\nf jumped into the cellar and called\nI on the foe to surrender.\nOut came a lieutenant and 20 men.\nhands in the air, guns on the ground\nbehind them.\nThree years later Hitler worked\nj the same bluff again, this time single\nj handed. He captured a French dug\nj out.\nIn neither case did he use violence.\nHe only threatened to use it.\nHis success was prophetic.\nTwo Violent Steps.\nThe two false steps in his climb to\npolitical power were violent steps:\n1. His beer cellar \"putsch\" in Mu\nnich, which ended with the death of\nhis henchmen and his own imprison\nment in 1923.\n2. The assassination of Chancellor\nEngelbert Dollfuss of Austria by Hit\nler's Nazi followers in Vienna in 1934.\nFor the rest, he only threatened vio\nlence. That was all he needed to do.\nFor he timed his moves like a genius.\nEverything he did was expected long\nbefore it happened.\nHis plans were international ru\nmors, and other nations discussed in\nadvance what they would do \u201cif.\u201d\nBut Hitler never acted while the\nworld was poised in readiness. He\nbided his time, then struck.\nNone to Stop Him.\nEvery nation that could have stopped\nhim when he renounced the Versailles\ntreaty and openly began rearmament\nof Germany in 1935 was tangled up\nin troubles of its own at the hour he\nchose to move.\nItaly, which had forestalled Ger\nman intervention in Austria by send\ning soldiers through the Brenner Pass\nafter Dollfuss\u2019 death the year before,\nhad her hands full now with the Ethi\nopian venture.\nEngland had hinted her unwilling\nness to fight some time before by let\nting it be known she favored German\nrelease from the arms restrictions of\nVersailles if Hitler would sign an arms\npact.\nFrance was torn internally by the\npolitical aftermath of the Stavisky\nscandal. An attempt to copy Ameri\nca's \"N. R. A.\u201d was meeting strong\nopposition. Fascists were stirring up\ntrouble. And the cabinet had a tax\nstrike on its hands.\nRussia was busy negotiating with\nJapan over Manchukuoan border in\ncidents.\nSo Hitler calmly announced that\nthe treaty of Versailles no longer ap\nplied, and that he planned to quadru\nple his army. The world grumbled,\nbut did nothing.\nStruck Twice More.\nBefore the other powers could re\ncover from that blow he struck twice\nmore in rapid succession.\nHe announced, through his right\nhand man, Hermann Goering, that\nGermany had an air force.\nThen, using Japan's renunciation of\nthe 5\u20145\u20143 ratio of the last World\nNaval Conference as a curb, he sent\nemissaries to England and negotiated\nan agreement whereby he increased\nhis sea power.\nThis time the other nations did not\nKremlin government seem ridiculous\nand impairing the faith of the masses\nin it.\u201d\nMr. Troyanovsky was asked, in view\nof Soviet \u201creadiness to defend itself\nagainst aggression and Fascism,\u201d what\nattitude of the Kremlin government\nwould be in the event Hitler followed\nup his annexation of Austria with a\nthrust at Czechoslovakia.\n\"Our policy is crystal-clear on this\nissue,\u201d the Soviet Ambassador an\nswered. \"By our treaties we are duty\nbound to come to the aid of Czecho\nslovakia militarily as soon as France\ndecides to give her such aid. And we\nhave always lived up to our treaties.\u201d\n(CopjrUht. 1038. b\u00bb the North American\nNewspaper Alliance, Inc.)\nv\nADOLF HITLER.\nworry him. He knew that in naval\nmatters England's word was Europe's\nlaw.\nHitler applied the same masterly\nstrategy in 1936.\nEngland was involved in sanctions\nagainst Italy's Ethiopian aggression.\nShe had one eye on the Far East in\nfear of the results of the recent mili\ntary coup in Japan. At home, she\nwas in the midst of an argument over\nincreased defenses. Abroad, she was\ndemanding satisfaction from Italy for\nthe bombing of the British Red Cross\nin Africa.\nJoint Policy Sought.\nFrance had asked Britain to formu\nlate a policy of joint action in event\nHitler made a new move, and Britain\nhad not replied. Paris was trying to\nquiet unrest in the French colAnies.\nThe Syrians were demanding inde\npendence. Premier Flandin was plead\nOregon Cruise\nAround Horn Is\nMarked Quietly\nThe Navy yesterday observed quietly\nthe 40th anniversary of the start of\nthe famous cruise of the battleship\nOregon around Cape Horn in 1898, as\nresearchers brought to light the fact\nher commanding officer, then Capt.\nCharles E. Clark, U. S. N\u201e could have\nstayed at Rio de Janeiro, had he\nwished, instead of putting his ship\nthrough the grueling test of going on\nto Key West, Fla.\nIn his memoirs, Admiral Clark\u2014\nfor he was later promoted\u2014quoted\ncable dispatches in which the Navy\nDepartment advised him he could pre\ntend to be making boiler and other\nrepairs at Rio. But he preferred to\nbrave further danger, after he learned\nthere the United States ahd Spain\nhad declared war, officials recalled.\nAdmiral Clark was well known in\nWashington, as are his two daughters,\nboth of whom married naval officers\nwho achieved the highest rank.\nOne of them is Mrs. Caroline Russell\nHughes, widow of the late chief of\nnaval operations, Rear Admiral\nCharles Frederick Hughes, who held\nthe rank of full admiral shortly before\nhis retirement from active service in\nNovember, 1930. Their daughter,\nLouisa Russell, is the wife of Comdr.\nOtto Nimitz,* U. S. N\u201e now on duty\nwith the Midvale Steel Co., Philadel\nphia, as inspector of naval ordnance.\nAdmiral Clark's. other daughter,\nMary Louise, married Rear Admiral\nSamuel S. Robison, who was a mem\nber of the General Board at the Navy\nDepartment in 1923. They now live\nat Admiral Farragut Academy, Toms\nRiver, N. J. He was superintendent of\nthe Naval Academy, Annapolis, Md\u201e\nand retired in 1931. Mrs. Hughes\nlives with Admiral and Mrs. Robison.\nENTERS G. 0. P. RACE\nWinter Haven Han Seeks Seat\nin Senate Held by Pepper.\nTALLAHASSEE, Fla., March 19 (JP).\n\u2014Allen E. Walker of Winter Haven\nbecame today the first Republican\ncandidate in Florida to seek State\nwide office through the May primaries.\nHe qualified with the Secretary of\nState to run for United States Senator\nClaude Pepper's seat. Five are seek\ning the Democratic nomination.\nCorrespondent to Speak.\nSlavko Nadin Serick, Washington\ncorrespondent for several newspapers\nin the Balkan States, will speak on\nHitler's Influence In Europe at the\nweekly luncheon meetiing of the Op\nportunity House Tuesday at 12:30 p.m.\nat the house.\nArthur Clarendon Smith will pre\nside. and Mrs. Helene McMahon, di\nrector of the Opportunity House, will\nreport on the agency\u2019s activities.\ne\nmg with Mussolini to make peace with\nHaile Selassie.\nRussia was fighting the Japanese in\nOuter Mongolia, and debating with\nTokio over renewal of fishing agree\nments.\nItaly was still embroiled in Ethiopia.\nSo Hitler calmly marched his sol\ndiers into the Rhineland. Again the\nworld grumbled. Again it did noth\ning but gesture.\nThen came Austria and 1938.\nEngland had just reversed its for\neign policy and lost its foreign min\nister. Anthony Eden, in a cabinet\nfight which ended on a note of friend\nship with the dictators. She was in\nthe preliminary stages of negotiations\nwith Italy.\nFrance was embogged in an in\nternal crisis over financing of rearma\nment.\nRussia Rendered Ineffertive.\nRussia, upon whom France depend\ned if England should fail her, was\nabsorbed in her third and largest\ntreason trial, and Stalin's \u201cpurge'\u2019\napparently was still continuing.\nItaly was now a part of the Ber\nlin-Rome axis and had shown .10\ndisposition to interfere when Hitler\ncalled Chancellor Schuschnigg to re\nceive the German ultimatum. Be\nsides. there still was disorder in\nEthiopia, and Mussolini was maneu\nvering for as strong a position as\npossible in the projected Italo-Eng\nlish accord a position greatly\nstrengthened by his friendship with\nHitler.\nSo Hitler calmly announced that\nAustria was no more.\nThe impotent grumbling which fol\nlowed was still rolling around the\nworld when Hitler spoke to the Reichs\ntag yesterday.\nHis speech was a warning that he\nintended to \"protect\u201d Germans in\nother lands.\nToday Czechoslovakia, caught in\nthe jaws of the Nazi vise which\nGermany and Austria form, moved to\ngive its 3.000.000 German citizens a\nproportionate share in local and na\ntional government.\nAs easy as that. Hitler did it.\nIn chess, you would put it this way:\nHe had the position and the move.\nQUEBEC PRINTER STRIKE\nARBITRATOR APPOINTED\nWalkout Had Forced Five\nNewspapers to Suspend\nPublication.\nBy the Associated Press.\nQUEBEC. March 19.\u2014The Quebec\nLabor Department today appointed\nan arbitrator to seek settlement of a\nprinters\u2019 strike which forced five daily\nnewspapers to suspend regular publi\ncation.\nThe strike was called by members\nof the International Typographical\nUnion, who asked a pay tncrease of\n$2 a week and a 44-hour week. Pres\nent minimum rates were announced\nby one newspaper to be $30.50 for a\n48-hour week for day workers and\n$32.50 for night employes working 45\nhours.\nAbout 250 printers were on strike\nagainst the 1'Evenement and Le Jour\nnal, morning newspapers; Le Soleil,\nChronicle-Telegraph and Le Quotidien\nde Levis, evening papers. The latter\nis published in the city of Levis, Just\nacross the St. Lawrence River.\nBesides the newspapers, a half dozen\ncommercial printing shops were af\nfected.\nALABAMA POLL TUESDAY\nSecond District to Name House\nSuccessor to Senator Hill.\nMONTGOMERY, Ala., March 19\n\u2014Alabama's nine-county second con\ngressional district will choose a House\nsuccessor Tuesday to Senator Lister\nHill of Montgomery, elevated to the\nSenate to replace Supreme Court Jus\ntice Hugo L. Black.\nContestants are R. T. Goodwyn, sr..\nMontgomery attorney and former\nlegislator, and George Grant, Troy\nlawyer and sportsman.\nWhile Tuesday's voting will be in a\nspecial Democratic primary, nomina\ntion is tantamount to election. The\nHill term will expire next January.\nBoth men, lauding major objectives of\nthe Roosevelt administration, have\nqualified for the 1939-40 term to be\ndecided in regular party primaries\nMay 3.\nI Am Solving Your\nlOc-per-Day Problem of\nPARKING\nWill Take 50 Cars ot\n3.00 Per Month\nHENDERSON'S\n457 Eye N.W., near Cor. 5th St.\nfir it Comt, Firit SirviJ\nA\nSoviet Pact Abandonment\nMay Be Bargaining\nSubject, However.\nBy the Associated Press.\nPRAHA, March 19.\u2014Adolf Hitler\nwas said by diplomatic sources today\nto have demanded that Czechoslovakia\nabandon her military alliance with\nSoviet Russia\u2014but the Czech govern\nment showed no Indication it would\ncomply.\nHitler\u2019s demand was said to have\nconstituted Der Fuehrer\u2019s basic con\ndition for talking terms with the little\nrepublic, now two-thirds surrounded\nby the expanded Reich.\nCzechoslovakia\u2019s existence virtually\nrests on her alliances with Russia and\nFrance, apart from sturdy reliance on\nher own military resources.\nSoviet Pact Never Popular.\nThe Russian alliance never has been\nextremely popular, and if Germany\noffers good compensation, political\ncircles believe there might be some re\norganization of Czech policy.\nHitler\u2019s long-expected move, said to\nhave been made through diplomatic\nchannels, came as the Czech govern\nment capitulated to another German\ndemand.\nBy action of the cabinet council,\nthe 3,500,000 Germans in Czechoslo\nvakia were given a greater voice in\nthe war-created republic's government.\nThe move permits administration of\nGerman districts by\u2018German nationals.\nIn Mood to Compromise.\nAlthough the concession apparently\nwould not satisfy completely the Czech\nGermans, headed by 39-year-old Kon\nrad Henlein, it was evident Czech\nleaders were in the mood to compro\nmise.\nThe haste with which they an\nnounced the administrative measure\nindicated that. Although the Czech\ngovernment insisted the measure was\nunder preparation a long time, an\nnouncement at this time was signifi\ncant.\nThe Henlein party has aemained\nsilent thus far, but Czech govern\nment circles do not expect Heinleln\nto be satisfied with the steps already\ntaken. A typical Nazi, Heinleln may\nbe expected to hold out for all or\nnothing, unless Hitler deems it advis\nable for him to compromise.\nAutonomy Held Impossible.\nGovernment circles said political\nautonomy for Sudeten Germans was\nimpossible for three reasons:\nFirst, in only a few border towns\nIs there a clear German majority. In\nmost Sudeten regions Germans and\nCzechs are mixed.\nSecond, to give autonomy to the\nGermans would be to erect a state\nwothin a state.\nThird, and worst of all from the 1\nviewpoint of democratic Czecho\nslovakia, a state within a state would\nhave an authoritarian government\nwhich would deny the very principles\non which the republic is founded.\nReady to Settle Otherwise.\nBarring only autonomy, the Czech\ngovernment Ls willing to settle the\nGerman minorities question in an\namicable manner. Czech statesmen\ndo not hesitate to acknowledge mis\ntakes have been made in the past.\nThey are confident the Nazi gov\nernment, too. will give the Czech gov\nernment credit for sincere good will\nin the hope Hitler will exert a re\nstraining influence upon radical Nazis\nled by Henlein.\nMeanwhile, the Czechs were fixing\ntheir fences at home. Dr. Frank\nJezek. deputy representing the Na\ntional Union, one of the most con\nservative Czech parties, was an\nnounced as minister without port\nfolio. The National Union thus far\nhas been in the opposition.\nJezek is to organize the new min\nistry of economics. With his entry\ninto the government all Czech parties\nexcept Communists and Fascists now\ni are in coalition.\nLITHUANIA ANGRY\nYIELDING TO POLES\nParliament in Reluctant\nApproval of Cabinet\u2019s\nSubmission.\nBy the Associated Press.\nKAUNAS, Lithuania, March 19.\u2014\nLithuania surrend\u00abd in advance today\nto the Polish bayonet* on her bor\nder, yielding angrily to Poland's ul\ntimatum to prevent blood-spilling.\nHer Parliament, in a special ses\nsion, heard the government announce\nit already had been \"forced\" to ex\ntend its unwilling hand in diplomatic\n\"friendship.\" The decision was re\nceived in stony silence in Parlia\nment.\nBut the legislators had no alterna\ntive except to indorse the govern\nment's compliance with Poland\u2019s\nterms\u2014an exchange of Ministers by\nMarch 31 and re-establishment of\nrail, postal and other relations.\nLithuania's forced friendship ended\na feud of 18 years. The i.sue came\nto a crisis after a Polish guard was\nkilled March 11 on the armed fron\ntier between the neighbors.\nBitterness Sweeps Country.\nA wave of bitterness spread through\nthe little Baltic country in whose lap\nsuddenly had been dumped her own\nand possibly Europe\u2019s peace. Despite\ngovernment efforts to calm the na\ntion and suppress demonstrations the\nsettlement Increased bitter anti-Polish\nfeeling.\nLithuanians generally believed they\nhad been forced to choose between\ntwo evils. They regarded acceptance\nof the ultimatum as a surrender to\nPolish threats of invasion behind\nwhich lurked the greater menace of a\nGerman coup in Memel, Lithuania's\nseaport.\n(In Berlin the German govern\nment reacted favorably to the\nLithuanian capitulation. Indica\ntions were that Reichsfuehrer Hit\nler would \"sit tight\u201d awhile before\nattempting any new move.i\nLithuania\u2019s capitulation amounts to\nvirtual admission that Wilno, which\nher constitution still claims as cap\nital. is Polish. Although Lithuania\ndid not formally renounce her claim\nthe Polish demand insisted there be\n\"no discussion\u201d of Wilno.\n\u201cA preponderance of force is on the\nside of Poland.\" Acting Premier\nJokuba.s Stanisauckis told Parliament.\n\"Might is not right. However, un\nder these circumstances, the Lithua\nnian government decided to submit\nto the Polish demands.\u201d The Legisla\nture reluctantly approved.\nNote Sent by Way of Estonia.\nEven before the Parliament met,\nthe Lithuanian Minister at Tallinn.\nEstonia, had handed a note to Poland's\nenvoy there announcing Lithuania's\ncapitulation.\nAt that moment, 100.000 Polish\ntroops\u2014five times more than Lithua\nnia's whole army\u2014were mobilized\nnear the frontier and the prows of\nPolish warships were pointed at Lith\nuania's Baltic shores.\nStanisauckis thanked the great\npowers which \"strived to help Lithu\nania in her hour of great stress.\u201d\nBritain, Prance and Russia had\nmade urgent representations to both\ngovernments to seek an amicable\nsolution, warning all Europe\u2019s peace\nmight be in the balance.\nSome sources though the bitterness\nwithin Lithuania might find expres\nsion in the resignation of three or\nfour ministers who held out against\nwhat they considered humiliation.\nAmong them was the Lithuanian for\neign minister. Stasys Lozoraitis. The\nsurrender, in fact, jeopardized the ex\nistence of the entire government.\nNation Is Stunned.\nThe bulk of the nation still was\ntoo stunned to react sharply to sub\nmission under pressure to a country\nit regards as an hereditary enemy.\nBut the semi-military Riflemen's\nLEARN TO FLY\nIN THE THE ONLY\nGOVERNMENT\nAPPROVED\nGROUND\nSCHOOL\nClass Starts\nTuesday\nrl\u201e. Evening.\nFirst Class March 22\nThis Year\n15 LESSONS\n1. Civil Air regulations\u20145 hours.\n2. Meteorology and navigation\u201420 hours.\nS. Servicing of Aircraft\u20145 hours.\nBRINCKERHOFF\nFLYING SERVICE, INC.\nCOLLEGE PARK AIRPORT\nCollege Park, Md. GReennood 1053\nQuaker City Linoleum Co.v\nN.W. Cor 6th F Sts. N.W. MEt. 1882\nWashington\u2019s Largest Linoleum Store\nPRICES SLASHED\nGENUINE TREADLITE RUBBER CUSHION\nINLAID LINOLEUM\nLAID and CEMENTED to Your FLOOR FREE\nIF YOU PURCHASE 10 SqJ\nYDS. OR MORE. PAT\nTERNS AND COLORS!\nFOR EVERY ROOm|\nA SLIGHT EXTRA CHARGE FOR\nINSTALLATION OF BATH ROOMS\nAMAZING SPECIAL OFFER\nHEAVIEST QUALITY\nH-INCH GUAGE\nARMSTRONG\u2019S and SEALEX\nINLAID UNOLEUM\nEmbotied and\nm Straight Line\nr Pattern*, Tile,\n111 Modern.\nBlock*\ni and Marble*\n^\u25a0MAt^M\u00aeiTioNA^cHA*e^o^LAirnf^0r^ettiBNTnio^^^i\nI\nUnion, with about 55,000 members,\nvirtually an auxiliary of the army,\nand student bodies began to voice deep\nresentment.\nThis was fed by reports in reliable\nquarters that Stanlsauckis yielded\nonly after a vain appeal to Soviet\nRussia for aid in resisting the Poles.\nRecognition that hopes of Russian\nIntervention were badly founded, it\nwas believed, might force a radical\nchange in Lithuania\u2019s foreign policy\ntoward appeasement with Poland.\nPAN-AMERICAN MEDICAL\nASSOCIATION TO MEET\nDiplomats, Physicians to Attend\nSession at Glenview Farm,\nHome of Dr. J. A. Lyon.\nAttended by diplomats and about\n100 physicians, the Washington Chap\nter of the Pan-American Medical As\nsociation will meet tonight at 8 o\u2019clock\nto hear addresses by leading special\nists.\nThe session will be held at the home\nof Dr. James Alexander Lyon, \u201cGlen\nview Farm,\u201d Rockville.\nThe Ambassador of Mexico, Dr. P.\nCastillo Najero, is president of the\nWashington Chapter of the associa\ntion. Other diplomats who have ac\ncepted invitations are the Ambassador\nof Cuba and the Ministers of Pan\nama, Honduras, El Salvador and Nica\nragua.\nDr. J. J. Eller, director general of\nthe association, who is a noted New\nYork dermatologist, will tell about the\ncruise of the Pan-American Medical\nAssociation in 1938 and plans for the\nBuenos Aires Congress.\nNO WAR FOR AMERICA,\nSENATOR LEWIS SAYS\nNew Tax Syatem Freeing Business\nof Its Present Burdens Also\nIs Predicted.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO, March 19.\u2014James Ham\nilton Lewis, Illinois\u2019 senior Senator,\ncame to Chicago for a visit today and\nmade these topical comments:\n\u201cThe United states will not be\ndrawn into any war.\n\u201cIn a month there will be a new\ntax system releasing business from the\nsurtaxes, the profit taxes and all bur\ndens now laid on business.\n\u201cThere will be no experimental legis\nlation, nor dictated policies that go\nagainst prosperity and business ad\nvance.\n\u201cThe United States, soon to be as\nsured of peace within itself, is on the\nway to the greatest business revival\nenjoyed for years.\u201d\nTO ADDRESS ALUMNI\nBishop Moore Will Tell of Needs\nat Handolph-Macon.\nBishop Arthur J. Moore of the\nMethodist Episcopal Church South\nwill speak on the needs of Randolph\nMacon College at 8 pm. Wednesday\nat the Mount Vernon Place Methodist\nChurch.\nThe address by Bishop Moore is\npart of a program launched by alumni\nand friends of the college to increase\npublic Interest in the college and to\nraise $200,000 with which to erect\na building on the campus.\n-There*8 Only One Answer\n\u2014to the true music-lovers and artists\nlonging for the best piano! It is\nSTEINWAY\n\u2022THE INSTRUMENT OF THE IMMORTALS\"\nGenerous Terms on the\nnew Steinway Baby Grand\nPiano. Price_ 1\nBecause of its great durability,\nit i3 the safest piano investment.\nIt will serve for a lifetime.\nDROOP\u2019S 1300 G\nHammond electric Organ\n\u201cThe Inetrument of a Million and More Tone Colore\"\nIDEAL TOR HOME CHURCH STUDIO CLUB\nSIMPLE to inetall ae a radio. Juet\nconnect it with any electric light\noutlet. The tonal pitch ie perfect and Priced From!\ncannot vary. Not affected by tempera\nture and humidity. Ite epeed of action\nie the epeed of light. IT HAS NO\nPIPES. CANNOT GET OUT OF\nTUNE. Ite volume ie unlimited. It\noccupiee leee space than a baby grand\npiano.\nWe\u2019re Clad to Play It For You Any Time. Come, See It!\nLet our Engineering Department tub\nmit plani and coit for 